<DOC><DOCNO> AP890801-0165 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1908EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-01 0546</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0560</SECOND><HEAD>Remnants Of Chantal Drench Southeast Texas</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Southeast Texas was hit with a deluge of rain _ 8{ inches at onespot _ from the remnants of Hurricane Chantal and thunderstormsswept through the lower Mississippi Valley to the southern AtlanticCoast on Tuesday.   Chantal hit southeast Texas on Tuesday morning and weakened to atropical storm. At 3 p.m. EDT, the center of the storm was 25 milesnorth of Houston and moving northwest at 12 mph.   Maximum sustained winds decreased to 55 mph, with higher gustsin squalls mainly over the Gulf of Mexico to the south of thecenter. The storm was expected to weaken as it moved further inland.   In addition to strong winds, torrential rains were reportedacross southeast Texas. More than 7 inches of rain fell atFriendswood and Houston Tuesday morning, with 4 inches dumped inone hour. Clear Lake City was drenched by 8{ inches of rain, whileGalveston received 6\ inches.   Widespread street flooding was reported throughout Brazoria,Fort Bend, Galveston and southern Harris Counties in southeastTexas. Access roads and underpasses on Interstate 45, nearDickinson, were flooded and several roads were closed. Highway 6was flooded near Arcola and Sugarland and widespread streetflooding was reported at Rosenburg.   Flash flood watches were in effect for southeast Texas and theupper Texas coast, as well as southwest central and southeastsections of Louisiana. Ten to 15 inches of rain were possibleacross parts of eastern Texas, with 3 to 5 inches possible overparts of central and southern Louisiana.   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Tuesday afternoon fromthe southern Plains across the lower Mississippi Valley to thesouthern half of the Atlantic Coast. Showers and thunderstorms werealso scattered over western Montana, with showers along the OregonCoast.   A flash-flood watch was posted for the northwest mountains ofWyoming because of possible heavy rains and flooding of creeks andstreams.   In southwest Virginia, thunderstorms brought heavy rain throughChristiansburg and Shawsville.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded nearly 7\ inches at Houston, and 4} inches at EllingtonAir Force Base and Galveston, Texas.   In the northern Plains, however, sunny and hot weatherprevailed. Readings were in the 90s over extreme eastern Montana,North Dakota and much of South Dakota.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59degrees at Astoria, Ore., to 106 degrees at Needles, Calif.Tuesday's low in the Lower 48 states was 33 degrees at Truckee,Calif.   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstormsthrough central and eastern Texas and southeast Oklahoma; scatteredshowers and thunderstorms through west Texas, the rest of Oklahoma,and from the lower Mississippi Valley across Alabama to the southAtlantic coastal states; scattered showers and thunderstorms fromthe northern Pacific Coast to Montana, from central Nebraska acrosseastern South Dakota and northwest Iowa to Minnesota, and fromnorthern New York to western New England; and thunderstormsscattered from North Dakota to Wyoming.   Temperatures were forecast in the 70s through northern NewEngland, the Pacific Northwest and along the California Coast;between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and90s throughout the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>